#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:3
msgid "Signature file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:5
msgid ""
"The interface definition file (.pyf) is how you can fine-tune the interface "
"between Python and Fortran. The syntax specification for signature files (``."
"pyf`` files) is modeled on the Fortran 90/95 language specification. Almost "
"all Fortran standard constructs are understood, both in free and fixed "
"format (recall that Fortran 77 is a subset of Fortran 90/95). F2PY "
"introduces some extensions to the Fortran 90/95 language specification that "
"help in the design of the Fortran to Python interface, making it more "
"\"Pythonic\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:13
msgid ""
"Signature files may contain arbitrary Fortran code so that any Fortran 90/95 "
"codes can be treated as signature files. F2PY silently ignores Fortran "
"constructs that are irrelevant for creating the interface. However, this "
"also means that syntax errors are not caught by F2PY and will only be caught "
"when the library is built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:21
msgid ""
"Currently, F2PY may fail with some valid Fortran constructs. If this "
"happens, you can check the `NumPy GitHub issue tracker <https://github.com/"
"numpy/numpy/issues>`_ for possible workarounds or work-in-progress ideas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:26
msgid ""
"In general, the contents of the signature files are case-sensitive. When "
"scanning Fortran codes to generate a signature file, F2PY lowers all cases "
"automatically except in multi-line blocks or when the ``--no-lower`` option "
"is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:31
msgid "The syntax of signature files is presented below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:34
msgid "Signature files syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:37
msgid "Python module block"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:39
msgid ""
"A signature file may contain one (recommended) or more ``python module`` "
"blocks. The ``python module`` block describes the contents of a Python/C "
"extension module ``<modulename>module.c`` that F2PY generates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:46
msgid ""
"Exception: if ``<modulename>`` contains a substring ``__user__``, then the "
"corresponding ``python module`` block describes the signatures of call-back "
"functions (see :ref:`Call-back arguments`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:50
msgid "A ``python module`` block has the following structure::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:52
msgid ""
"python module <modulename>\n"
"  [<usercode statement>]...\n"
"  [\n"
"  interface\n"
"    <usercode statement>\n"
"    <Fortran block data signatures>\n"
"    <Fortran/C routine signatures>\n"
"  end [interface]\n"
"  ]...\n"
"  [\n"
"  interface\n"
"    module <F90 modulename>\n"
"      [<F90 module data type declarations>]\n"
"      [<F90 module routine signatures>]\n"
"    end [module [<F90 modulename>]]\n"
"  end [interface]\n"
"  ]...\n"
"end [python module [<modulename>]]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:71
msgid ""
"Here brackets ``[]`` indicate an optional section, dots ``...`` indicate one "
"or more of a previous section. So, ``[]...`` is to be read as zero or more "
"of a previous section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:77
msgid "Fortran/C routine signatures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:79
msgid "The signature of a Fortran routine has the following structure::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:81
msgid ""
"[<typespec>] function | subroutine <routine name> \\\n"
"              [ ( [<arguments>] ) ] [ result ( <entityname> ) ]\n"
"  [<argument/variable type declarations>]\n"
"  [<argument/variable attribute statements>]\n"
"  [<use statements>]\n"
"  [<common block statements>]\n"
"  [<other statements>]\n"
"end [ function | subroutine [<routine name>] ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:90
msgid ""
"From a Fortran routine signature F2PY generates a Python/C extension "
"function that has the following signature::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:93
msgid ""
"def <routine name>(<required arguments>[,<optional arguments>]):\n"
"     ...\n"
"     return <return variables>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:97
msgid "The signature of a Fortran block data has the following structure::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:99
msgid ""
"block data [ <block data name> ]\n"
"  [<variable type declarations>]\n"
"  [<variable attribute statements>]\n"
"  [<use statements>]\n"
"  [<common block statements>]\n"
"  [<include statements>]\n"
"end [ block data [<block data name>] ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:110
msgid "Type declarations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:112
msgid "The definition of the ``<argument/variable type declaration>`` part is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:117
msgid "<typespec> [ [<attrspec>] :: ] <entitydecl>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:119 ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:175
#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:193 ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:234
msgid "where"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:123
msgid ""
"<typespec> := byte | character [<charselector>]\n"
"           | complex [<kindselector>] | real [<kindselector>]\n"
"           | double complex | double precision\n"
"           | integer [<kindselector>] | logical [<kindselector>]\n"
"\n"
"<charselector> := * <charlen>\n"
"               | ( [len=] <len> [ , [kind=] <kind>] )\n"
"               | ( kind= <kind> [ , len= <len> ] )\n"
"<kindselector> := * <intlen> | ( [kind=] <kind> )\n"
"\n"
"<entitydecl> := <name> [ [ * <charlen> ] [ ( <arrayspec> ) ]\n"
"                      | [ ( <arrayspec> ) ] * <charlen> ]\n"
"                     | [ / <init_expr> / | = <init_expr> ] \\\n"
"                       [ , <entitydecl> ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:138
msgid "and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:140
msgid "``<attrspec>`` is a comma separated list of attributes_;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:142
msgid "``<arrayspec>`` is a comma separated list of dimension bounds;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:144
msgid "``<init_expr>`` is a :ref:`C expression <c-expressions>`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:146
msgid ""
"``<intlen>`` may be negative integer for ``integer`` type specifications. In "
"such cases ``integer*<negintlen>`` represents unsigned C integers;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:150
msgid ""
"If an argument has no ``<argument type declaration>``, its type is "
"determined by applying ``implicit`` rules to its name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:154
msgid "Statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:157
msgid "Attribute statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:159
msgid ""
"The ``<argument/variable attribute statement>`` is similar to the "
"``<argument/variable type declaration>``, but without ``<typespec>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:162
msgid ""
"An attribute statement cannot contain other attributes, and ``<entitydecl>`` "
"can be only a list of names. See :ref:`f2py-attributes` for more details on "
"the attributes that can be used by F2PY."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:167
msgid "Use statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:169
msgid "The definition of the ``<use statement>`` part is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:173
msgid "use <modulename> [ , <rename_list> | , ONLY : <only_list> ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:179
msgid "<rename_list> := <local_name> => <use_name> [ , <rename_list> ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:181
msgid ""
"Currently F2PY uses ``use`` statements only for linking call-back modules "
"and ``external`` arguments (call-back functions). See :ref:`Call-back "
"arguments`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:185
msgid "Common block statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:187
msgid "The definition of the ``<common block statement>`` part is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:191
msgid "common / <common name> / <shortentitydecl>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:197
msgid "<shortentitydecl> := <name> [ ( <arrayspec> ) ] [ , <shortentitydecl> ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:199
msgid ""
"If a ``python module`` block contains two or more ``common`` blocks with the "
"same name, the variables from the additional declarations are appended.  The "
"types of variables in ``<shortentitydecl>`` are defined using ``<argument "
"type declarations>``. Note that the corresponding ``<argument type "
"declarations>`` may contain array specifications; then these need not be "
"specified in ``<shortentitydecl>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:207
msgid "Other statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:209
msgid ""
"The ``<other statement>`` part refers to any other Fortran language "
"constructs that are not described above. F2PY ignores most of them except "
"the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:213
msgid ""
"``call`` statements and function calls of ``external`` arguments (see :ref:"
"`more details on external arguments <external>`);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:226
msgid "``include`` statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:219
msgid ""
"include '<filename>'\n"
"include \"<filename>\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:222
msgid ""
"If a file ``<filename>`` does not exist, the ``include`` statement is "
"ignored. Otherwise, the file ``<filename>`` is included to a signature "
"file.  ``include`` statements can be used in any part of a signature file, "
"also outside the Fortran/C routine signature blocks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:247
msgid "``implicit`` statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:231
msgid ""
"implicit none\n"
"implicit <list of implicit maps>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:238
msgid "<implicit map> := <typespec> ( <list of letters or range of letters> )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:240
msgid ""
"Implicit rules are used to determine the type specification of a variable "
"(from the first-letter of its name) if the variable is not defined using "
"``<variable type declaration>``.  Default implicit rules are given by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:247
msgid "implicit real (a-h,o-z,$_), integer (i-m)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:264
msgid "``entry`` statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:252
msgid "entry <entry name> [([<arguments>])]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:254
msgid ""
"F2PY generates wrappers for all entry names using the signature of the "
"routine block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:259
msgid ""
"The ``entry`` statement can be used to describe the signature of an "
"arbitrary subroutine or function allowing F2PY to generate a number of "
"wrappers from only one routine block signature. There are few restrictions "
"while doing this: ``fortranname`` cannot be used, ``callstatement`` and "
"``callprotoargument`` can be used only if they are valid for all entry "
"routines, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:267
msgid "F2PY statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:269
msgid "In addition, F2PY introduces the following statements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:273
msgid "``threadsafe``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:272
msgid ""
"Uses a ``Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS .. Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS`` block around the "
"call to Fortran/C function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:281
msgid "``callstatement <C-expr|multi-line block>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:276
msgid ""
"Replaces the  F2PY generated call statement to Fortran/C function with ``<C-"
"expr|multi-line block>``. The wrapped Fortran/C function is available as "
"``(*f2py_func)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:280
msgid ""
"To raise an exception, set ``f2py_success = 0`` in ``<C-expr|multi-line "
"block>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:291
msgid "``callprotoargument <C-typespecs>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:284
msgid ""
"When the ``callstatement`` statement is used, F2PY may not generate proper "
"prototypes for Fortran/C functions (because ``<C-expr>`` may contain "
"function calls, and F2PY has no way to determine what should be the proper "
"prototype)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:288
msgid ""
"With this statement you can explicitly specify the arguments of the "
"corresponding prototype::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:291
msgid ""
"extern <return type> FUNC_F(<routine name>,<ROUTINE NAME>)"
"(<callprotoargument>);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:300
msgid "``fortranname [<actual Fortran/C routine name>]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:294
msgid ""
"F2PY allows for the use of an arbitrary ``<routine name>`` for a given "
"Fortran/C function. Then this statement is used for the ``<actual Fortran/C "
"routine name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:298
msgid ""
"If ``fortranname`` statement is used without ``<actual Fortran/C routine "
"name>`` then a dummy wrapper is generated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:322
msgid "``usercode <multi-line block>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:303
msgid ""
"When this is used inside a ``python module`` block, the given C code will be "
"inserted to generated C/API source just before wrapper function definitions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:307
msgid ""
"Here you can define arbitrary C functions to be used for the initialization "
"of optional arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:310
msgid ""
"For example, if ``usercode`` is used twice inside ``python module`` block "
"then the second multi-line block is inserted after the definition of the "
"external routines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:314
msgid ""
"When used inside ``<routine signature>``, then the given C code will be "
"inserted into the corresponding wrapper function just after the declaration "
"of  variables but before any C statements. So, the ``usercode`` follow-up "
"can contain both declarations and C statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:319
msgid ""
"When used inside the first ``interface`` block, then the given C code will "
"be inserted at the end of the initialization function of the extension "
"module. This is how the extension modules dictionary can be modified and has "
"many use-cases; for example, to define additional variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:331
msgid "``pymethoddef <multiline block>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:325
msgid ""
"This is a multi-line block which will be inserted into the definition of a "
"module methods ``PyMethodDef``-array. It must be a comma-separated list of C "
"arrays (see `Extending and Embedding`__ Python documentation for details).  "
"``pymethoddef`` statement can be used only inside ``python module`` block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:336
msgid "Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:338
msgid "The following attributes can be used by F2PY."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:350
msgid "``optional``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:341
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is moved to the end of ``<optional arguments>`` "
"list. A default value for an optional argument can be specified via "
"``<init_expr>`` (see the ``entitydecl`` :ref:`definition <type-"
"declarations>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:347
msgid "The default value must be given as a valid C expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:348
msgid ""
"Whenever ``<init_expr>`` is used, the ``optional`` attribute is set "
"automatically by F2PY."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:350
msgid "For an optional array argument, all its dimensions must be bounded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:360
msgid "``required``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:353
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument with this attribute is considered mandatory. This "
"is the default. ``required`` should only be specified if there is a need to "
"disable the automatic ``optional`` setting when ``<init_expr>`` is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:357
msgid ""
"If a Python ``None`` object is used as a required argument, the argument is "
"treated as optional. That is, in the case of array arguments, the memory is "
"allocated. If ``<init_expr>`` is given, then the corresponding "
"initialization is carried out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:364
msgid "``dimension(<arrayspec>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:363
msgid ""
"The corresponding variable is considered as an array with dimensions given "
"in ``<arrayspec>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:514
msgid "``intent(<intentspec>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:367
msgid ""
"This specifies the \"intention\" of the corresponding argument. "
"``<intentspec>`` is a comma separated list of the following keys:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:373
msgid "``in``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:371
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is considered to be input-only. This means that "
"the value of the argument is passed to a Fortran/C function and that the "
"function is expected to not change the value of this argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:390
msgid "``inout``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:376
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is marked for input/output or as an *in situ* "
"output argument. ``intent(inout)`` arguments can be only :term:`contiguous` "
"NumPy arrays (in either the Fortran or C sense) with proper type and size. "
"The latter coincides with the default contiguous concept used in NumPy and "
"is effective only if ``intent(c)`` is used. F2PY assumes Fortran contiguous "
"arguments by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:385
msgid ""
"Using ``intent(inout)`` is generally not recommended, as it can cause "
"unexpected results. For example, scalar arguments using ``intent(inout)`` "
"are assumed to be array objects in order to have *in situ* changes be "
"effective. Use ``intent(in,out)`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:390
msgid "See also the ``intent(inplace)`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:403
msgid "``inplace``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:393
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is considered to be an input/output or *in situ* "
"output argument. ``intent(inplace)`` arguments must be NumPy arrays of a "
"proper size. If the size of an array is not \"proper\" or the array is non-"
"contiguous then the routine will be passed a fixed copy of array, which has "
"the :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEBACKIFCOPY` flag set, so that the result will be "
"copied back to the original array on exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:402
msgid ""
"Since copies may be made, ``intent(inplace)`` can be slower than expected. "
"It is recommended over ``inout``, but not over ``in,out``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:413
msgid "``out``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:406
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is considered to be a return variable. It is "
"appended to the ``<returned variables>`` list. Using ``intent(out)`` sets "
"``intent(hide)`` automatically, unless  ``intent(in)`` or ``intent(inout)`` "
"are specified as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:411
msgid ""
"By default, returned multidimensional arrays are Fortran-contiguous. If "
"``intent(c)`` attribute is used, then the returned multidimensional arrays "
"are C-contiguous."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:422
msgid "``hide``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:416
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is removed from the list of required or optional "
"arguments. Typically ``intent(hide)`` is used with ``intent(out)`` or when "
"``<init_expr>`` completely determines the value of the argument like in the "
"following example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:421
msgid ""
"integer intent(hide),depend(a) :: n = len(a)\n"
"real intent(in),dimension(n) :: a"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:442
msgid "``c``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:425
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is treated as a C scalar or C array argument. For "
"the case of a scalar argument, its value is passed to a C function as a C "
"scalar argument (recall that Fortran scalar arguments are actually C pointer "
"arguments).  For array arguments, the wrapper function is assumed to treat "
"multidimensional arrays as C-contiguous arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:431
msgid ""
"There is no need to use ``intent(c)`` for one-dimensional arrays, "
"irrespective of whether the wrapped function is in Fortran or C. This is "
"because the concepts of Fortran- and C contiguity overlap in one-dimensional "
"cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:436
msgid ""
"If ``intent(c)`` is used as a statement but without an entity declaration "
"list, then F2PY adds the ``intent(c)`` attribute to all arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:440
msgid ""
"Also, when wrapping C functions, one must use ``intent(c)`` attribute for "
"``<routine name>`` in order to disable Fortran specific ``F_FUNC(..,..)`` "
"macros."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:448
msgid "``cache``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:445
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is treated as junk memory. No Fortran nor C "
"contiguity checks are carried out. Using ``intent(cache)`` makes sense only "
"for array arguments, also in conjunction with ``intent(hide)`` or "
"``optional`` attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:454
msgid "``copy``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:451
msgid ""
"Ensures that the original contents of ``intent(in)`` argument is preserved. "
"Typically used with the ``intent(in,out)`` attribute. F2PY creates an "
"optional argument ``overwrite_<argument name>`` with the default value ``0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:459
msgid "``overwrite``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:457
msgid ""
"This indicates that the original contents of the ``intent(in)`` argument may "
"be altered by the Fortran/C function.  F2PY creates an optional argument "
"``overwrite_<argument name>`` with the default value ``1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:463
msgid "``out=<new name>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:462
msgid ""
"Replaces the returned name with ``<new name>`` in the ``__doc__`` string of "
"the wrapper function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:483
msgid "``callback``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:466
msgid ""
"Constructs an external function suitable for calling Python functions from "
"Fortran. ``intent(callback)`` must be specified before the corresponding "
"``external`` statement. If the 'argument' is not in the argument list then "
"it will be added to Python wrapper but only by initializing an external "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:474
msgid ""
"Use ``intent(callback)`` in situations where the Fortran/C code assumes that "
"the user implemented a function with a given prototype and linked it to an "
"executable. Don't use ``intent(callback)`` if the function appears in the "
"argument list of a Fortran routine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:479
msgid ""
"With ``intent(hide)`` or ``optional`` attributes specified and using a "
"wrapper function without specifying the callback argument in the argument "
"list; then the call-back function is assumed to be found in the  namespace "
"of the F2PY generated extension module where it can be set as a module "
"attribute by a user."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:492
msgid "``aux``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:486
msgid ""
"Defines an auxiliary C variable in the F2PY generated wrapper function. "
"Useful to save parameter values so that they can be accessed in "
"initialization expressions for other variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:492
msgid "``intent(aux)`` silently implies ``intent(c)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:494
msgid "The following rules apply:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:496
msgid ""
"If none of ``intent(in | inout | out | hide)`` are specified, ``intent(in)`` "
"is assumed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:499
msgid "``intent(in,inout)`` is ``intent(in)``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:501
msgid "``intent(in,hide)`` or ``intent(inout,hide)`` is ``intent(hide)``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:503
msgid ""
"``intent(out)`` is ``intent(out,hide)`` unless ``intent(in)`` or "
"``intent(inout)`` is specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:506
msgid ""
"If ``intent(copy)`` or ``intent(overwrite)`` is used, then an additional "
"optional argument is introduced with a name ``overwrite_<argument name>`` "
"and a default value 0 or 1, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:510
msgid "``intent(inout,inplace)`` is ``intent(inplace)``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:512
msgid "``intent(in,inplace)`` is ``intent(inplace)``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:514
msgid "``intent(hide)`` disables ``optional`` and ``required``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:525
msgid "``check([<C-booleanexpr>])``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:517
msgid ""
"Performs a consistency check on the arguments by evaluating ``<C-"
"booleanexpr>``; if ``<C-booleanexpr>`` returns 0, an exception is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:522
msgid ""
"If ``check(..)`` is not used then F2PY automatically generates a few "
"standard checks (e.g.  in a case of an array argument, it checks for the "
"proper shape and size). Use ``check()`` to disable checks generated by F2PY."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:540
msgid "``depend([<names>])``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:528
msgid ""
"This declares that the corresponding argument depends on the values of "
"variables in the ``<names>`` list. For example, ``<init_expr>`` may use the "
"values of other arguments.  Using information given by ``depend(..)`` "
"attributes, F2PY ensures that arguments are initialized in a proper order. "
"If the ``depend(..)`` attribute is not used then F2PY determines dependence "
"relations automatically. Use ``depend()`` to disable the dependence "
"relations generated by F2PY."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:536
msgid ""
"When you edit dependence relations that were initially generated by F2PY, be "
"careful not to break the dependence relations of other relevant variables. "
"Another thing to watch out for is cyclic dependencies. F2PY is able to "
"detect cyclic dependencies when constructing wrappers and it complains if "
"any are found."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:544
msgid "``allocatable``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:543
msgid ""
"The corresponding variable is a Fortran 90 allocatable array defined as "
"Fortran 90 module data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:590
msgid "``external``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:549
msgid ""
"The corresponding argument is a function provided by user. The signature of "
"this call-back function can be defined"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:552
msgid "in ``__user__`` module block,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:553
msgid ""
"or by demonstrative (or real, if the signature file is a real Fortran code) "
"call in the ``<other statements>`` block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:556
msgid "For example, F2PY generates from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:558
msgid ""
"external cb_sub, cb_fun\n"
"integer n\n"
"real a(n),r\n"
"call cb_sub(a,n)\n"
"r = cb_fun(4)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:566
msgid "the following call-back signatures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:568
msgid ""
"subroutine cb_sub(a,n)\n"
"    real dimension(n) :: a\n"
"    integer optional,check(len(a)>=n),depend(a) :: n=len(a)\n"
"end subroutine cb_sub\n"
"function cb_fun(e_4_e) result (r)\n"
"    integer :: e_4_e\n"
"    real :: r\n"
"end function cb_fun"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:579
msgid "The corresponding user-provided Python function are then:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:581
msgid ""
"def cb_sub(a,[n]):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    return\n"
"def cb_fun(e_4_e):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    return r"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:590
msgid "See also the ``intent(callback)`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:595
msgid "``parameter``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:593
msgid ""
"This indicates that the corresponding variable is a parameter and it must "
"have a fixed value. F2PY replaces all parameter occurrences by their "
"corresponding values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:598
msgid "Extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:601
msgid "F2PY directives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:603
msgid ""
"The F2PY directives allow using F2PY signature file constructs in Fortran "
"77/90 source codes. With this feature one  can (almost) completely skip the "
"intermediate signature file generation and apply F2PY directly to Fortran "
"source codes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:608
msgid "F2PY directives have the following form::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:610
msgid "<comment char>f2py ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:612
msgid ""
"where allowed comment characters for fixed and free format Fortran codes are "
"``cC*!#`` and ``!``, respectively. Everything that follows ``<comment "
"char>f2py`` is ignored by a compiler but read by F2PY as a normal non-"
"comment  Fortran line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:618
msgid ""
"When F2PY finds a line with F2PY directive, the directive is first replaced "
"by 5 spaces and then the line is reread."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:621
msgid ""
"For fixed format Fortran codes, ``<comment char>`` must be at the first "
"column of a file, of course. For free format Fortran codes, the F2PY "
"directives can appear anywhere in a file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:628
msgid "C expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:630
msgid "C expressions are used in the following parts of signature files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:632
msgid "``<init_expr>`` for variable initialization;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:633
msgid "``<C-booleanexpr>`` of the ``check`` attribute;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:634
msgid "``<arrayspec>`` of the ``dimension`` attribute;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:635
msgid ""
"``callstatement`` statement, here also a C multi-line block can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:637
msgid "A C expression may contain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:639
msgid "standard C constructs;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:640
msgid "functions from ``math.h`` and ``Python.h``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:641
msgid ""
"variables from the argument list, presumably initialized before according to "
"given dependence relations;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:643
msgid "the following CPP macros:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:645
msgid "``f2py_rank(<name>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:646
msgid "Returns the rank of an array ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:647
msgid "``f2py_shape(<name>, <n>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:648
msgid "Returns the ``<n>``-th dimension of an array ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:649
msgid "``f2py_len(<name>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:650
msgid "Returns the length of an array ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:651
msgid "``f2py_size(<name>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:652
msgid "Returns the size of an array ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:653
msgid "``f2py_itemsize(<name>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:654
msgid "Returns the itemsize of an array ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:657
msgid "``f2py_slen(<name>)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:656
msgid "Returns the length of a string ``<name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:659
msgid ""
"For initializing an array ``<array name>``, F2PY generates a loop over all "
"indices and dimensions that executes the following pseudo-statement::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:663
msgid "<array name>(_i[0],_i[1],...) = <init_expr>;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:665
msgid ""
"where ``_i[<i>]`` refers to the ``<i>``-th index value and that runs from "
"``0`` to ``shape(<array name>,<i>)-1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:668
msgid ""
"For example, a function ``myrange(n)`` generated from the following signature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:671
msgid ""
"subroutine myrange(a,n)\n"
"  fortranname        ! myrange is a dummy wrapper\n"
"  integer intent(in) :: n\n"
"  real*8 intent(c,out),dimension(n),depend(n) :: a = _i[0]\n"
"end subroutine myrange"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:679
msgid "is equivalent to ``numpy.arange(n,dtype=float)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:683
msgid ""
"F2PY may lower cases also in C expressions when scanning Fortran codes (see "
"``--[no]-lower`` option)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:687
msgid "Multi-line blocks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:689
msgid ""
"A multi-line block starts with ``'''`` (triple single-quotes) and ends with "
"``'''`` in some *strictly* subsequent line.  Multi-line blocks can be used "
"only within .pyf files. The contents of a multi-line block can be arbitrary "
"(except that it cannot contain ``'''``) and no transformations (e.g. "
"lowering cases) are applied to it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:695
msgid "Currently, multi-line blocks can be used in the following constructs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:697
msgid "as a C expression of the ``callstatement`` statement;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:699
msgid "as a C type specification of the ``callprotoargument`` statement;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:701
msgid "as a C code block of the ``usercode`` statement;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:703
msgid "as a list of C arrays of the ``pymethoddef`` statement;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:705
msgid "as documentation string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:708
msgid "Extended char-selector"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:710
msgid ""
"F2PY extends char-selector specification, usable within a signature file or "
"a F2PY directive, as follows::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:713
msgid ""
"<extended-charselector> := <charselector>\n"
"                        | (f2py_len= <len>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/signature-file.rst:716
msgid "See :ref:`Character Strings` for usage."
msgstr ""
